To check if a window is closed before calling `ShowDialog()`, you can use the `IsLoaded` property of the `Window` class. When the window is closed, `IsLoaded` will be set to `false`, so you can check this property to ensure that the window is still open before calling `ShowDialog()`.

Here's an example code snippet:

```
private void ButtonOpenWindow_Click(object sender, RoutedEventArgs e)
{
    MyWindow window = new MyWindow();

    if (window.IsLoaded)
    {
        // Window is still open, so call ShowDialog()
        window.ShowDialog();
    }
    else
    {
        // Window is closed, so create a new instance and call ShowDialog()
        window = new MyWindow();
        window.ShowDialog();
    }
}
```

In this example, we first create an instance of the window. Then we check the `IsLoaded` property to see if the window is still open. If it is, we call `ShowDialog()` on the existing instance. If it is not, we create a new instance and call `ShowDialog()` on that.

This way, you can ensure that `ShowDialog()` is only called on open windows to avoid the error you encountered earlier.

